      <h3>
        Side note: Framing of questions - what are letter carriers reporting on?
      </h3>
      <p>
        Most letter carriers will not have undergone the necessary training to
        be able to make observations pertaining to medical conditions. Thus
        interpretations pertaining mood, appetite, and other lifestyle choices
        can be largely subjective and fluctuating based on letter carrier.
      </p>
      <p>
        As we do not wish to place expectations on letter carriers without
        proper training to be able to correctly interpret the health conditions
        of older adults, the questions they would be required to answer are
        framed so they would be centred around objective observations, which
        allow the families and recipients to interpret the observations based on
        their knowledge.
      </p>
      <h3>Resources for unexpected events & emergencies</h3>
      <p>
        To alleviate the pressure on postal carriers to be experts on handling
        risks that are outside of their expertise, would allow them to maintain
        their focus on this service's core strategy, on preventing social
        isolation. The 'resources' tab will act as a manual to answer questions
        such as 'what do I do if the recipient is not answering the door'; the
        'report an emergency' tab will connect the letter carrier to the
        appropriate emergency service, such as the police or the ambulance.
      </p>
