  <h2>Business opportunities</h2>

  <h3>1. "The Great Mail Decline"</h3>
  <p>
    In their 
    <a href="https://www.canadapost-postescanada.ca/cpc/en/our-company/financial-and-sustainability-reports/2022-annual-report/our-financial-results.page">
      2022</a>
    and 
    <a href="https://www.canadapost-postescanada.ca/cpc/en/our-company/financial-and-sustainability-reports/2023-annual-report/executive-summary.page"
>2023 financial reports</a>, Canada Post has revealed that letter delivery
    has been on the decline since 2005. In the parcel delivery space, they have been losing market share
    to faster, cheaper competitors such as FedEx or UPS. As a response, the crown
    corporation seeks to extend its offerings beyond traditional postage services.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Keeping up with the world</h3>
  <p>
    We find that this is a global trend shared with postal services in other
    countries.
    <a
      href="https://www.newyorker.com/culture/annals-of-inquiry/in-france-elder-care-comes-with-the-mail"
      >The New Yorker</a
    >
    has identified at least five other countries, including not only Japan and France,
    but even the United States, which offer successful check-in services, some of
    which are even more extensive than our proposed Carriers That Care.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Integration with other parts of the business</h3>
  <p>
    While we acknowledge that implementation of this service alone would not
    resolve Canada Post’s declining revenues, my team and I still believe that
    it would benefit the business in the way of opening new avenues for income.
    In Jersey, their check-in service is funded by their Department of Health
    and Community Services. Furthermore, in cases such as with the U.K’s Royal
    Mail Health, where customers may connect to a pharmacist or GP and have
    prescriptions delivered to their door, expansion of services has allowed for
    partnerships with large-scale pharmaceutical companies. Partnerships with
    government and other corporations are just a few ways that Canada Post could
    leverage Carriers That Care as a revenue source.
  </p>

